      <hedline>
        <hl1>Prague Under The Influence</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Ken Martin letter on Evan Rail's March 25 travel article on 36-hour visit to Prague</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor: The Travel section continues to underestimate the intelligence of its readers.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor: The Travel section continues to underestimate the intelligence of its readers.</p>
        <p>If I followed Evan Rail's suggestions from ''36 Hours: Prague'' (March 25), I'd be drunk by lunchtime on Saturday and at a loss on how to spend the rest of the day, since 8 of the 10 suggestions involve food and drink. The only museum on the list is treated as an afterthought: the paintings at the Museum of Czech Cubism are to be checked out only after a visit to the Grand Caf√© Orient housed in the building.</p>
        <p>My only other options would be to visit ''cutting-edge boutiques'' that sell ''vibrant, coarse-knit skirts and cropped sweaters'' or to climb a boulder at the top of Petrin Hill.</p>
        <p>Why? So that I might fall off and land on top of the pile of injured, stuffed, similarly inebriated Americans?</p>
        <p>Ken Martin  San Francisco</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
